<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>A</m> an <m>n\times n</m> matrix.
      We define its <term>square</term>
      to be the matrix <m>A^2:=AA</m>.
    </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            In real number algebra we know that <m>a^2=0\implies a=0</m>. By contrast, show
            that there are infinitely many <m>2\times 2</m> matrices <m>A</m> satisfying <m>A^2=\boldzero_{2\times 2}</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Optional: can you describe in a parametric manner the set of <em>all</em> matrices <m>A</m> satisfying <m>A^2=\boldzero_{2\times 2}</m>?
          </p>

        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            In real number algebra we know that <m>a^2=a\implies a=0 \text{ or } a=1</m>. By contrast, show
            that there are infinitely many <m>2\times 2</m> matrices <m>A</m> satisfying <m>A^2=A</m>.
          </p>

        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            In real number algebra we have the identity <m>(x+y)^2=x^2+2xy+y^2</m>. Show that two <m>n\times n</m> matrices <m>A</m>, <m>B</m> satisfy
            <me>
              (A+B)^2=A^2+2AB+B^2
            </me>
            if and only if <m>AB=BA</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
  </statement>
  <hint>
    <p>
       For (a) set <m>A=\abcdmatrix{a}{b}{c}{d}</m>, compute <m>A^2</m>, set this matrix equal to <m>\boldzero_{2\times 2}</m>, and try and find some solutions to the corresponding (nonlinear) system of four equations in the unknowns <m>a,b,c,d</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Similar hint for (b), only now set <m>A^2=A</m>.
    </p>
  </hint>
</exercise>
